comments.message:
Use power to power cycle is better to use reset pin

otii_device.set_main(False)
sleep(1)
otii_device.set_main(True)
otii_device.set_main_voltage(3.7)
otii_device.set_exp_voltage(1.8)
otii_device.set_gpo(2, True)
these commands have been done in create_otii when creating the otii_device,   Will we need to redo it again ?

it depends how we want to do the power cycle, 
we can do it through(otii_device.set_gpo(2, False), otii_device.set_gpo(2, True)) This is same as we press the reset button on the board,

We can also do it through (otii_device.set_main(False), otii_device.set_main(True)) This is same we power on/ off the module(re-plug the power cable)

I think through set_main will do a more complete power cycle while set_gpo just press the reset button.But both can work
Agreed. Should do 25 seconds? SWI_Reset_Module default booting duration is 25s
Change has been successfully merged by Kaiyu Yang

comments.message: this function is overlap with get_pending_operation_uids.  In fact, if necessary, in the future we may need a new function called get_operation_state(self, job_uid) which can be used to check the specific job_uid.

I'm not too sure what you mean, which part is overlapping?

-get_pending_operation_uids() returns list of uids (i.e. 357bc30283cd44cbb9f3e5c5faa7a988)
-get_pending_operation_state() returns the list of operation states (i.e. CANCELLED, IN_PROGRESS, SUCCESS, etc)
is the pending operation status always be "IN_PROGRESS"?

No, depending on the state of the task, it can be any of the following:

-PENDING
-IN_PROGRESS
-BEING_CANCELLED
-CANCELLED
-FAILURE
-SUCCESS

now i see your point.
So two comments:
1. the function name should be call get_operation_state
2. job_uid should not set as list as this function only deal with job_uid[0]
one uid can only return one state, so why we set state as list?
